class Solution {
    public int numIslands(char[][] grid) {
        int count = 0;
        for(int i=0; i < grid.length; i++){
            for(int j=0; j < grid[0].length; j++){
                if(grid[i][j] == '1'){
                    dfs(grid, i, j);
                    count++;
                }
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
    private void dfs(char[][] grid, int x, int y){
        if(x >= 0 && y >= 0 && x < grid.length && y < grid[0].length && grid[x][y] == '1'){
            grid[x][y] = '0';
            dfs(grid, x-1, y);
            dfs(grid, x+1, y);
            dfs(grid, x, y-1);
            dfs(grid, x , y+1);
        }
    }
}

ðŸ”¹ Time Complexity: O(M Ã— N)
Let:
M = grid.length (number of rows)
N = grid[0].length (number of columns)
Reasoning:
You visit each cell in the grid at most once.
When a cell is '1', DFS marks it '0', and you never visit it again.
The outer loops check every cell once â†’ M Ã— N iterations.
The DFS explores adjacent cells but only visits unvisited land cells once.
âœ… Each cell contributes a constant amount of work (push + pop + mark).
So total time = O(M Ã— N).


ðŸ”¹ Space Complexity
Two parts to consider:
1ï¸âƒ£ Recursive call stack (DFS depth)
In the worst case, if the entire grid is land ('1' everywhere), the recursion could go as deep as M Ã— N.
So, recursive stack space = O(M Ã— N) (worst case).
2ï¸âƒ£ Input modification
You modify grid in-place (no extra visited matrix).
Hence no additional memory except recursion stack.
âœ… Space = O(M Ã— N) in worst case (recursion depth).
If you used an explicit stack (iterative DFS or BFS), itâ€™d also be O(M Ã— N) in queue/stack space.
